# CLAUDE.md — coding agent guide for this repo

You are implementing a GitHub issue in a **client-facing** production repo for
Omni Strive. The bar is "professional, neat, and works on a client's phone the
first time they open the link." Prioritize correctness and polish over
cleverness or scope.

## Stack

- Framework: Next.js (App Router), TypeScript, React Server Components by default
- Styling: Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui ("new-york" style, `neutral` base, CSS
  variables in `app/globals.css`, `cn()` from `@/lib/utils` for class merging)
- Icons: `lucide-react` only — do not add another icon library
- Data / auth: Supabase (Postgres + Auth + RLS) via `@supabase/ssr`
- Hosting: Vercel

## Commands

- Install: `npm install`
- Dev: `npm run dev`
- Build (**always run before finishing**): `npm run build`
- Lint: `npm run lint`
- Test: run it if a test command exists in `package.json`; otherwise skip

## Before you write code

- Read the issue's acceptance criteria fully before touching files.
- Look at 2-3 neighboring files (same folder, same kind of component) and match
  their patterns exactly — naming, file layout, import order, prop shapes.
- Check `components/ui/` for an existing primitive before building a new one.
  Compose from `Button`, `Card`, `Input`, `Label`, `Badge`, `Checkbox`,
  `DropdownMenu`, etc. Only add a new `components/ui/*` primitive if nothing
  close exists — and build it in the same style (`React.forwardRef`,
  `class-variance-authority` for variants, `cn()` for class merging, Radix
  primitive under the hood when there's interaction/a11y to get right).
- Reuse existing color tokens (`bg-background`, `text-foreground`,
  `text-muted-foreground`, `border-border`, `bg-card`, `bg-primary`, etc.) and
  `--radius`-based rounding (`rounded-lg` / `rounded-md` / `rounded-sm`).
  Never hardcode hex colors or inline styles when a token exists.

## Responsive: mobile-first, always

Every screen you touch must look intentional from a 393px-wide iPhone up
through a desktop monitor — this is non-negotiable, most client traffic is
mobile.

- Write unprefixed Tailwind classes for the smallest screen first, then layer
  `sm:` / `md:` / `lg:` for larger viewports. Never design desktop-first and
  hope it degrades.
- Use fluid layout primitives (`flex`, `grid`, `gap-*`, `w-full`,
  `max-w-*` + `mx-auto`) over fixed pixel widths.
- Touch targets are at least 40px tall on mobile (shadcn's default `h-9`/`h-10`
  button sizes are the floor, not the ceiling — don't shrink them further).
- Test your own mental model against 393px, 768px, and 1280px before calling a
  layout done. If you can't run a browser, reason explicitly about how a flex
  row of 3+ items or a wide table behaves at 393px, and wrap/stack accordingly.
- Tables and wide content: wrap in `overflow-x-auto` rather than letting the
  page itself scroll horizontally.

## Text and content safety

Client and user-generated text is unpredictable length — a long email, a long
project name, a pasted paragraph. Every place dynamic text renders must
survive it without breaking layout:

- Long unbroken strings: add `break-words` (or `break-all` for things like
  raw URLs/tokens) so they wrap instead of overflowing their container.
- Flex/grid children holding text need `min-w-0` so they can actually shrink;
  without it, text forces siblings off-screen.
- Truncate intentionally with `truncate` (single line) only when the full text
  is available elsewhere (title attribute, detail view, tooltip) — don't
  silently drop information with no way to see the rest.
- Never assume a name, title, or description fits on one line at any width.

## Accessibility

- Use semantic HTML (`button` for actions, `a` for navigation, one `h1` per
  page, real `label`/`Label` for every form input).
- Every interactive element needs a visible focus state — don't strip the
  `focus-visible:ring-*` styles already built into the `ui/` primitives.
- Icon-only buttons need an `aria-label` (or visually-hidden text) describing
  the action, not just the icon.
- Maintain readable contrast — stick to the existing token pairs
  (`bg-*`/`text-*-foreground`) rather than inventing new color combinations.
- Images need meaningful `alt` text (or `alt=""` if purely decorative).

## Spacing and typography consistency

- Use the Tailwind spacing scale (`p-4`, `gap-6`, `space-y-1.5`, etc.) — don't
  invent arbitrary values like `mt-[13px]` unless matching an existing
  pixel-perfect spec.
- Match existing type scale and weight patterns already in the codebase
  (e.g. `CardTitle`'s `font-semibold leading-none tracking-tight`,
  `CardDescription`'s `text-sm text-muted-foreground`) instead of picking new
  sizes per component.
- Keep consistent vertical rhythm within a page — reuse the same section
  spacing (`space-y-6`, `py-6`, etc.) already used elsewhere in that area of
  the app rather than eyeballing new numbers.

## Data and Supabase

- Never invent or bypass Row Level Security — write queries assuming RLS is
  on, and add/update policies only if the issue calls for a schema change.
- Do not commit secrets, `.env*` files, or hardcode API keys/URLs — use
  `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_*` / server-only env vars consistent with existing
  usage.
- Prefer Server Components and server-side data fetching; only add
  `"use client"` where interactivity actually requires it.

## Scope and dependencies

- Implement only what the issue asks for. No unrelated refactors, renames, or
  "while I'm here" cleanups — open a note in the PR description instead.
- Do not add a new npm dependency unless the issue genuinely requires
  capability nothing in `package.json` already provides. If you do, explain
  why in the PR description.
- Do not touch CI config, environment variables/secrets, or delete data.
- Do not run destructive commands (`rm -rf`, force pushes, DB drops).

## Definition of done

- [ ] Every acceptance criterion in the issue is satisfied.
- [ ] Layout is verified (or reasoned through) at mobile (393px), tablet
      (~768px), and desktop (~1280px) widths.
- [ ] Dynamic/long text can't break the layout (`break-words`, `min-w-0`,
      `truncate` used where relevant).
- [ ] Interactive elements are keyboard-reachable with visible focus and
      correct labels.
- [ ] New UI reuses existing `components/ui/*` primitives and design tokens —
      no stray colors, ad hoc spacing, or duplicate components.
- [ ] `npm run build` passes with no errors before you open the PR.
- [ ] The change is scoped to the issue; no unrelated files touched, no new
      dependencies unless justified in the PR body.
- [ ] The PR description explains what changed, how it was verified, and
      calls out anything a human still needs to do (e.g. "final copy TBD",
      "needs a Supabase migration run").
